5. Operational Definition

A pattern counts as Pantheon-real when it satisfies enough of the following:
	1.	Compression Survival
It can be reduced without losing core structure.
	2.	Expansion Recovery
It can be re-expanded into a useful form after compression.
	3.	Translation Stability
It remains recognizable across languages, metaphors, modalities, or implementations.
	4.	Pressure Tolerance
It does not immediately shatter under contradiction, adversarial testing, or reframing.
	5.	Temporal Continuity
It remains useful across time rather than only in one momentary state.
	6.	Cross-Domain Resonance
It reappears in multiple domains without becoming meaningless.
	7.	Practical Reusability
It can guide action, interpretation, or design.

If these hold, the pattern is not guaranteed to be ultimate truth.
But it is stable enough to enter the build stack.

