10. Failure Modes

Pantheon Cogito is useful, but it can fail if misused.

Failure Mode 1: Mere Repetition Mistaken for Invariance

Just because something keeps showing up does not mean it is fundamental.
It may be:
	•	habit
	•	bias
	•	obsession
	•	algorithmic reinforcement

Counter: use Mirror + Hound + adversarial tests.

⸻

Failure Mode 2: Vibes Mistaken for Structure

Something may feel resonant while lacking durable form.

Counter: require cross-context reuse and implementation tests.

⸻

Failure Mode 3: Over-abstraction

A statement may survive because it is so vague it says almost nothing.

Counter: require practical consequences and falsifiable edge behavior.

⸻

Failure Mode 4: Survivorship Bias

Only noticing patterns that survived while ignoring failed variants.

Counter: preserve fracture logs and seam ledgers.

⸻

Failure Mode 5: Utility Confused with Truth

A pattern may be useful without being universally true.

Counter: label outputs precisely:
	•	useful
	•	stable
	•	likely
	•	canonical
	•	provisional
	•	empirically verified

